isis.stitle: Recall 05508-R1 - DRIVELINE on certain RE School and Commercial Bus models with IROS Suspension built between 01-28-2003 and 03-09-2005

recall.subject: DRIVELINE on certain RE School and Commercial Bus models with IROS Suspension built between 01-28-2003 and 03-09-2005

defect.para: Information regarding adjusting the axle travel has been added to the end of the Service Procedure section (just below Figure 1).

para.exhotlnk: Print ready (PDF file) copy of the dealer letter
Print ready (PDF file) copy of the customer letter

defect.para: Excessive suspension travel may cause the u-joint straps or strap bolts on either end of the driveshaft to fail as a result of the high working angle. Failure of the u-joint straps will cause part or all of the driveshaft to fall off the bus. This may result in property damage, personal injury or death.
This recall involves certain RE School and Commercial Bus models with IROS Suspension built between 01-28-2003 and 03-09-2005.

ownernote.para: During the recall process a listing of owner names and addresses will be furnished to the involved dealers to enable dealers to follow up with owners and have the vehicles corrected. You must limit the use of this listing to this campaign because the list may contain information obtained from state motor vehicle registration records and the use of such motor vehicle registration data for purposes other than this campaign is a violation of law in several states.

svcprocinfo.para: The repair procedure required is dependent on the VIN of the bus. Only charges for the labor and parts that each VIN requires will be honored. See the VIN list (Table 2) for repair variation required.

para.emph: One of the following 5 repairs will be completed. These variations are VIN specific.

svcprocinfo.para: VARIATION 1 A REPLACE AXLE STOPS, REPLACE SHOCKS, REVERSE ORIENTATION OF DRIVESHAFT (TURN END FOR END) AND REPLACE U-JOINT STRAPS.
VARIATION 1 B REPLACE AXLE STOPS, REPLACE SHOCKS, REPLACE DRIVESHAFT AND REPLACE U-JOINT STRAPS.
VARIATION 2 A REPLACE SHOCKS, REVERSE ORIENTATION OF DRIVESHAFT (TURN END FOR END) AND REPLACE U-JOINT STRAPS.
VARIATION 2 B REPLACE SHOCKS, REPLACE DRIVESHAFT AND REPLACE U-JOINT STRAPS.
VARIATION 3 REPLACE DRIVESHAFT AND REPLACE U-JOINT STRAPS
Driveshaft - the correct new orientation is

line.emph: Stub shaft = Male end: goes on axle end
Slip shaft = Female end: goes on transmission end

svcprocinfo.para: Not all VINs will have the driveshaft replaced. All VINs will have the driveshaft orientation changed OR the driveshaft replaced. The orientation described above should be the final orientation of the driveshaft.

Strap Kit - because the current driveshaft will be removed in all cases, all VINs will require the straps and strap bolts to be replaced. The correct strap kit will be determined by the current driveshaft if the driveshaft is re-oriented or by the new driveshaft if the driveshaft is replaced.

Shocks - these are the same for all VINs, which require shock replacement. Remember that the repair variation is VIN specific and not all VINs require new shocks. If this VIN also needs to have AFC 04909 performed and it has not been completed yet, the shock part number installed in this recall supersedes the shock part number installed in AFC 04909. If AFC 04909 has been completed, the shocks must still be replaced.
Axle Stops - these are the same for all VINs, which require axle stop replacement. Remember that the repair variation is VIN specific and not all VINs will require new axle stops.

warning.para: To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when you perform vehicle maintenance or service.
To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death when servicing the vehicle, park on a flat level surface, set the parking brake, turn the engine off and chock the wheels.

svcprocinfo.para: It is not necessary to jack the bus up to complete these procedures. BE SURE to use the new nuts or bolts that are supplied in the kits.

table.title: Strap Kit Required and Torque Value for Strap Bolts

step1.para: Check the orientation of the driveshaft before performing this step.
Remove u-joint strap bolts and strap at one end of the driveshaft.
Remove u-joint strap bolts and strap at other end of the driveshaft.
Reverse the driveshaft orientation end-for-end and attach using new straps and new bolts. The driveshaft should now be oriented as follows:

line.emph: Stub shaft = Male end: goes on axle end
Slip shaft = Female end: goes on transmission end

step1.para: Tighten the u-joint strap bolts with a torque wrench according to Table 1 based on the existing driveshaft part number.
Remove u-joint strap bolts and strap at one end of the driveshaft.
Remove u-joint strap bolts and strap at the other end of the driveshaft.
Attach new driveshaft using new straps and new bolts. The driveshaft will now be oriented as follows:

line.emph: Stub shaft = Male end: goes on axle end
Slip shaft = Female end: goes on transmission end

step1.para: Tighten the u-joint strap bolts with a torque wrench according to Table 1 based on the new driveshaft part number.
Remove left shock and replace with new shock using new bolts.
Torque left shock bolt to 148 - 177 LbF-Ft (200-240 Nm) using a torque wrench.
Remove right shock and replace with new shock using new bolts.
Torque right shock bolt to between 148 - 177 LbF-Ft (200-240 Nm) using a torque wrench.

svcsubproc.title: REPLACE LEFT AXLE STOP - Refer to Figure 1 below

step1.para: Remove Upper Nut and Upper Bolt that holds axle stop to frame rail.
Remove Lower Nut and Lower Bolt that holds axle stop to frame rail.
Replace axle stop with new one.
Replace the axle stop bolts and nuts with the new bolts and nuts that are included in the kit. Both bolts for the left side are the same length.
Torque the axle stop nuts to 196 - 239 LbF-Ft (266-324 Nm).

svcsubproc.title: REPLACE RIGHT AXLE STOP - Refer to Figure 1 below

step1.para: Remove Upper Nut and Upper Bolt that holds axle stop to frame rail.
Remove Lower Nut and Lower Bolt that holds axle stop and transverse torque rod to frame rail.

Replace the axle stop bolts and nuts with the new bolts and nuts that are included in the kit. Both bolts for the right side are NOT the same length. Use the longer bolt to replace the Lower Bolt that also holds the transverse torque rod to the frame.
Torque the axle stop nuts to 196 - 239 LbF-Ft (266-324 Nm).

svcsubproc.para: The axle stops are held to the frame rail by 2 sets of bolts and nuts that pass through the frame rail. Right side is shown in Figure 1 below. The proper position of the bolts and nuts is to place the bolts into the holes from the inside, so that the nuts are on the outside of the frame rail. This correct position allows sufficient access to the nuts for the torque operation.

*PLEASE NOTE: With the new, longer axle stops installed, the axle travel should now be set to 2.375 ± 0.125 inches in order to maintain proper ride height. IROS axle travel is measured from the bottom of the axle stop to the top of the U-bolt as illustrated in Figure 5 (IROS Axle Travel Measurement) in TSI 04-03-01.

responuscan.para:
Proceed immediately to make necessary correction to units in inventory. All inventory vehicles subject to this recall campaign must be corrected prior to sale, transfer or delivery.
If vehicles have been sold or transferred and you are in receipt of Customer Notification Letters and Authorization for Recall Service cards for those vehicles, transfer location or customer must be notified IMMEDIATELY from your dealer location.

Dealers must correct all vehicles subject to this campaign at no charge to the owner, regardless of mileage, age of vehicle, or ownership, from this time forward. The National Traffic and Motor Vehicle Safety Act, as amended, provides that each vehicle that is subject to a vehicle recall campaign must be adequately repaired within a reasonable time after the owner has tendered it for repair. A failure to adequately repair within 60 days after a tender of a vehicle is prima facie evidence of failure to repair within a reasonable time. If the condition is not adequately repaired within 60 days, the owner may be entitled to replacement with an identical or reasonable equivalent vehicle at no charge, or to a refund of the purchase price less a reasonable allowance for depreciation.

However, consistent with the customer notification, dealers are expected to complete the repairs on the mutually agreed upon service date. To avoid having to replace a vehicle or refund the purchase price, every effort must be made to promptly schedule an appointment with each owner to repair his or her vehicle as soon as possible.

There may be an occasion when a customer was charged for repairs related to this recall prior to the recall being released. The customer letter contains a statement for the customer to contact the Dealer if they believe they are entitled to reimbursement costs. The Dealer should follow the Customer Reimbursement guidelines in Warranty Policy Letter 03-001G. The Warranty Procedures and Administrative Policies manual (CTS1100) is in the process of being updated to include the information in Policy Letter 03-001G.
